english:
  title: Record of the New City Gate Tower of Heunghaejun
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Cross the bird ridge and venture southeast, traveling hundreds of li until the sea appears. There lies a county called Heunghaejun—a land remote and rugged, yet blessed with the riches of fishing, salt-making, and fertile soil. In ages past, it flourished with many inhabitants, but calamity came with the pirates' scourge. Decay descended gradually until the summer of Gyeongsin, when ruin struck most fiercely. The walls fell, flames consumed all, and the people faced slaughter and plunder nearly unto extinction. Those few who escaped scattered to the four directions. Villages became wastelands; briars choked the roads. Those appointed as magistrates dared not venture into the town itself, dwelling instead in distant hamlets—so it had been for years.

    When Jeongmyo arrived, the nation stationed warships south of the county seat at Tongyang Harbor to guard against raiders. Only then did scattered people begin returning, hearts drawn homeward. Yet without fortified walls, they could not gather and dwell securely. They excavated hide-aways in mountain valleys, desperate to conceal their traces, venturing out only to farm and fish. When raiders came, none could aid another—each scattered like mice into hiding. Thus magistrates remained in distant villages, still fearing to enter the county town.

    In the winter of Musin, Magistrate Zhao Yourliang of Gimje arrived on a single horse, pouring his heart into governance. By autumn of the following year, order flourished and the people found peace. He then asked the gathered elders: "Your county has no walls. The people remain unsettled. I wish to build and fortify them. Do you object?" All replied: "It is our fervent desire. Who would dare refuse?" He reported to the Inspector and requested laborers, but was denied. So he gathered the county's people—old and young, scarcely more than dozens—and began in the eighth month. With staff in hand, he supervised without rest, encouraging the diligent and warning the idle, showing neither leniency nor harshness. The people gladly rushed to the work. Commander Baek Ingwan of Tongyang contributed fifty soldiers to assist. By the tenth month, the work was complete.

    Thereafter the people could gather and build their homes. Day by day more returned from exile. That winter, Magistrate Zhao was transferred. The people loved and mourned him as a nursing child mourns its mother. They wished to record his deeds upon the gate tower, leaving their longing for him inscribed there, yet found no way. The following spring of Gyeonggo, I arrived here in exile.

    At that time Commander Baek served as magistrate, perfecting what Magistrate Zhao had left undone. He deepened the moat to strengthen the outer defenses and reinforced the gates to secure the inner stronghold. Thus the walls became yet more complete and formidable. The county's elders—An Seongeon, former prefect of Taizu; Zhang Biao, former commander; Li Hui, and others—spoke to me: "We were born and raised here, and now grow old here. Our magistrates change yearly or every other year; we have seen nearly countless numbers pass through. Yet among all who possessed both integrity and brilliance, whose authority inspired both fear and love, whom the people dared not deceive—never have we witnessed one to compare with Magistrate Zhao. And never has our county faced such devastation, nor such burdensome tasks and troublesome records, as in the days of the land survey. When Magistrate Zhao took office after such ruin, amid such disorder and difficulty, he came with but one servant and a single horse. His own living was austere. He reduced morning and evening provisions to aid the hungry and poor, arranging resources by every means to provide for official needs, never imposing a single tax upon the people. In surveying the fields, what his eye once beheld—the abundance or scarcity of plots, the richness or poorness of soil, the success or failure of harvests—he never forgot. Thus his records were swift and economical, precise and detailed beyond all other counties. Brave in repelling pirates, when word came of their approach, he mounted his horse and rode first to meet them. Twice the pirates came, yet could not invade. When using weak laborers numbering fewer than a hundred, he never struck a single soul, never extended labor beyond its season. He transformed briars into fortifications, turned wasteland into streets and homes, allowing our people to dwell secure as in old days, sleeping soundly without fear. From this day forward to all future generations, our families endure, our descendants thrive—all by the grace of our Magistrate Zhao. Thus we love him as parents and yearn for him as children long for their mother. Though years pass, we cannot forget. We beseech you to write his deeds in words, that those who come after may not forget the virtue of our Magistrate Zhao."

    Hearing this, I was moved. I recorded their words and spoke thus: "Did Mencius not say that favorable terrain matters less than harmony among people? The building of walls and digging of moats depends on human effort and commitment. Yet walls crumble and moats fill when those who tend them depart. Now the walls and moats are built, Magistrate Zhao's kindness already established. Will those who guard this land hereafter truly keep the people from departing? Might there not arise those who cause them to flee? This rests upon how well future magistrates win the people's hearts. If the people grow restless, cultivate their trust. If the walls weaken, repair them. Do not squander what has been achieved, but strive ever to build upon it."

    All rose and bowed, saying: "If your words guide us, our successive magistrates will only redouble their efforts, and our people's livelihood will remain secure. We beseech you to record this together in this memorial."

    Magistrate Zhao is descendant of the esteemed Zhao Gan. His grandfather was Minister Zhao Delie, whose virtue is praised to this day. Magistrate Zhao truly inherits their legacy. Should he one day rise to high office, we may trust he will not diminish his ancestors' accomplishments.

    Written in the twenty-third year of Hongwu, fifth month.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gyeongsin and Jeongmyo are sexagenary cycle year names. Gyeongsin refers to 1380, marking a major pirate invasion during the late Goryeo period. The timeline places this record in the early Joseon era.
  - key: ''
    value: Magistrate Zhao's lineage traces back to Zhao Gan (趙簡), an esteemed official, and his grandfather Zhao Delie (德烈), who served as Minister—establishing him as heir to a distinguished administrative tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The author Gwon Geun was an important Joseon statesman and scholar. His mention of arriving as an exile ('I came here in exile') reflects his historical fall from favor and subsequent exile.
  - key: ''
    value: Mencius's principle that 'favorable terrain is less important than harmony among people' (地利不如人和) serves as the philosophical foundation for the essay's argument that good governance depends on winning hearts, not fortifications alone.
